<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-131-666  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 131 666.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 20 1989 v23 n12 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Text retrieval finds its home; but relational DBMSs have troublewhen it comes to free-form data.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cortese, Amy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Full-text retrieval systems are expected to grow in popularity,with 1989 being a key year.andP;  Text retrieval systems, unlike mostdata base management systems (DBMS), can search and retrieve anyword or string of words in a textual database, eliminating theneed for users to know reference points, such as key words ornames of documents.andP;  Structured Query Language (SQL), which is thestandard language for most relational DBMSs, offers no provisionsfor text handling.andP;  Most relational DBMS vendors, however, aremaking extensions to SQL, or to their proprietary systems, toaccommodate text.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Storage and RetrievalData base management systemsText Data Bases.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Sales and projected sales of full-text retrieval systems,1987-1992. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>